# Hard Drive Problem

## Problem Description

Mad scientist Mike needs to read the data on m distinct tracks with numbers p_1, p_2,..., p_{m}. Determine the minimum time the hard drive firmware needs to move the heads and read all the given tracks.

## Solution

We can solve this problem by using a sweep line algorithm. The idea is to sweep the tracks from left to right and right to left, and keep track of the time when each track is visited.

### Code

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

typedef long long ll;

int main() {
    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;

    vector<ll> h(n), p(m);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> h[i];
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        cin >> p[i];
    }

    sort(h.begin(), h.end());
    sort(p.begin(), p.end());

    ll res = 0;
    int i = 0, j = m - 1;
    while (i < n) {
        ll head1 = h[i];
        ll head2 = h[i + 1];

        if (j >= 0) {
            ll head3 = p[j];
            if (head3 < head1) {
                ll pos = lower_bound(h.begin(), h.end(), head3) - h.begin();
                res += abs(pos - i);
                i = pos;
            }
        }

        if (i < n - 1) {
            ll head4 = h[i + 2];
            if (head4 > head2) {
                ll pos = lower_bound(h.begin(), h.end(), head4) - h.begin();
                res += abs(pos - i - 1);
                i = pos;
            }
        }

        j--;
    }

    cout << res << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

## Explanation

The algorithm works by maintaining two pointers, i and j, which represent the current positions of the two heads. We start by sorting the heads and tracks, and then iterate over the heads. For each head, we check if the corresponding track has been visited. If not, we move the head to the track and update the result.

We use the lower_bound function to find the position of the track in the sorted array of heads. This gives us the time when the track is visited.

We also handle the case where the head is at the end of the array, and the track is to the left of the head. In this case, we move the head to the track and update the result.

Finally, we move the head to the next position and repeat the process until all heads have been visited.

## Time Complexity

The time complexity of the algorithm is O(n log n + m log m), where n is the number of heads and m is the number of tracks. This is because we are sorting the heads and tracks, and then iterating over the heads.

## Space Complexity

The space complexity of the algorithm is O(1), which means the space required does not change with the size of the input.

